tters of dramaturgy. Tracing his extraordinary journey as a composer, the book shows how Weill’s artistic ambitions led to his working with a remarkably heterogeneous collection of authors, such as Georg Kaiser, Bertolt Brecht, Moss Hart, Alan Jay Lerner, and Maxwell Anderson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusical theaterxHistoryy20th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Composers & Musicians.2bisacsh  a20th century composers.  a20th century music.  a20th century musical theater.  a20th century opera.  aamerican entertainment.  aamerican music.  aamerican musical theater.  abroadway musicals.  aeuropean history.  aeuropean musicals.  aeuropean opera.  aeuropean theater.  afamous composers.  agerman composer.  ahistoric composers.  ahistory of broadway.  ahistory of opera.  ahistory of theater.  amusic and theater.  amusic studies.  amusical composers.  amusical fans.  amusical lovers.  amusicological study.  aperforming arts history.  atheatre biographies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027177740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095183940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951839423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520951839/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY